[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen. I'm Vishupriya Nair and Nikita Saxena. Nikita, I loved your report on Pachauri when it first came out.

00:04:22.440 --> 00:04:31.440
[Amit Varma]: And when I was reading it again today morning, it struck me that much of what you describe in that story is universally true of our culture.

00:04:31.440 --> 00:04:38.440
[Amit Varma]: The work environment where sexism is normalized, the persistent patterns of psychological and emotional manipulation, as you put it,

00:04:38.440 --> 00:04:43.440
[Amit Varma]: the gaslighting of the victims where they are made to feel as if there is something wrong with them and they are overreacting,

00:04:43.440 --> 00:04:51.440
[Amit Varma]: the act of victimhood by the accused when they are confronted with their actions, the use and misuse of power, which proves a dictum that power always corrupts.

00:04:51.440 --> 00:04:56.440
[Amit Varma]: What was it like reporting on the story for you as all these layers revealed themselves?

00:04:56.440 --> 00:05:11.440
[Guest 2]: So the story initially had sort of taken form at the time that the case that one of the survivors had filed in 2015 sort of started getting attention.

00:05:11.440 --> 00:05:17.440
[Guest 2]: And Raghav Ory, who was the journalist from Economic Times who broke the story, had doggedly been following it.

00:05:17.440 --> 00:05:28.440
[Guest 2]: And the idea initially was just to see in a short report what this journey for someone who tried to take recourse through due process looked like.

00:05:28.440 --> 00:05:35.440
[Guest 2]: I think by day two, we had a sense that we were actually looking at a way larger story.

00:05:35.440 --> 00:05:47.440
[Guest 2]: And for me, I think you really do not anticipate the kind of challenges you are going to be facing on reporting a story that has such direct repercussions for you.

00:05:47.440 --> 00:05:58.440
[Guest 2]: Because as a woman, to be reporting on multiple stories of sexual harassment also meant for me that I was revisiting a lot of my professional and personal experiences

00:05:58.440 --> 00:06:05.440
[Guest 2]: that I had for the longest time kept buried, which was not comfortable at all.

00:06:05.440 --> 00:06:16.440
[Guest 2]: But in a way, it also meant that with each interview, I was privileged with information and insight that I did not have earlier that also helped me navigate this space on my own.

00:06:16.440 --> 00:06:22.440
[Guest 2]: And I'd like to think that I was able to use that insight to report the story better.

00:06:22.440 --> 00:06:35.440
[Guest 2]: The other thing was just the repetitions and patterns to the point that it was almost banal.

00:06:35.440 --> 00:06:42.440
[Guest 2]: And that was what surprised me after a point because I remember sitting when I was just going to start writing.

00:06:42.440 --> 00:06:45.440
[Guest 2]: I sat with all the transcripts of my interviews and I'd done multiple interviews.

00:06:45.440 --> 00:06:54.440
[Guest 2]: And after a while, all of it on my desk started looking the same because he was following the same pattern with all of these women.

00:06:54.440 --> 00:06:59.440
[Guest 2]: It could have been at different points of time. There could have been different ways to enter the equation.

00:06:59.440 --> 00:07:04.440
[Guest 2]: But largely, when you sort of looked at it from the top, it didn't look very different.

00:07:04.440 --> 00:07:16.440
[Guest 2]: So, you know, one of the things was, for example, the young women that he chose to prey on or women who were coming from situations that would make them perceivably more vulnerable.

00:07:16.440 --> 00:07:23.440
[Guest 2]: So to kind of make use of the insecurities that professional women are anyway coming in with at any office.

00:07:23.440 --> 00:07:29.440
[Guest 2]: And this is something I think about often that it so happened that this story was of Terry.

00:07:29.440 --> 00:07:41.440
[Guest 2]: But the idea that men who make sexist jokes, who are known to make what they loosely call passes at women, which is such a trivialization of what actually happens.

00:07:41.440 --> 00:07:46.440
[Guest 2]: We all know those people in our offices and we all know men who condone those jokes.

00:07:46.440 --> 00:07:53.440
[Guest 2]: And we all have been complicit in not supporting women who may have wanted to come out with these complaints earlier.

00:07:53.440 --> 00:07:56.440
[Guest 2]: And I think that's a larger problem, not just a Terry problem.

00:07:56.440 --> 00:08:06.440
[Guest 2]: To come back to Pachauri, I mean, you know, so one was that you would see that there were a lot of young women that he decided to act as a mentor to.

00:08:06.440 --> 00:08:10.440
[Guest 2]: And for me, that was personally the most corrupting part of it.

00:08:10.440 --> 00:08:22.440
[Guest 2]: Right. Because all of these women would enter into their interactions with him, believing that they're being approached because of their intellect or because of what they bring to the organization.

00:08:22.440 --> 00:08:34.440
[Guest 2]: And then to be dehumanized at the point that you realize that it is all so that this man can approach you with, you know, a sexual intent or a gendered intent.

00:08:34.440 --> 00:08:53.440
[Guest 2]: I think to be to be listening to the recollection of that was the hardest, because that betrayal of trust or the betrayal of the idea that you were worthy of the attention, intellectual and professional of a man who you deeply admired isn't comparable.

00:08:53.440 --> 00:08:58.440
[Guest 2]: And that's the part, sorry, that I think we tend to overlook when we're talking about sexual harassment.

00:08:58.440 --> 00:09:13.440
[Guest 2]: It's not just the physical, you know, it's not just the physical transgressions. It's also the the breaking of the confidence of a woman trying to reinforce the idea that you are always going to be your gender.

00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:15.440
[Guest 2]: Sorry, Supriya, I think you were saying.

00:09:15.440 --> 00:09:20.440
[Guest 1]: I had a question. Can you tell us how many women you spoke to approximately through the course of the story?

00:09:20.440 --> 00:09:33.440
[Guest 2]: So I spoke to about 50 to 60 people for the story in its entirety and apart from three women, including the main complainant who had already put out their versions, either through a legal complaint or through open letters.

00:09:33.440 --> 00:09:41.440
[Guest 2]: I spoke to six women who were survivors. And this was over the course of the 30 years that Terry had started.

00:09:41.440 --> 00:09:47.440
[Guest 2]: So the oldest employee, so to speak, that I spoke to was someone who worked in Terry in the early 90s.

00:09:47.440 --> 00:09:54.440
[Guest 2]: So we're also talking about something that was allowed to continue for very long, for way longer than it should have.

00:09:54.440 --> 00:10:00.440
[Guest 2]: And the kind of devastation that this leaves the women with, you know.

00:10:00.440 --> 00:10:14.440
[Guest 2]: So, for example, I remember one woman telling me that she went into another office after she left Terry and she remembered immediately noticing that there are a lot of women in that office and that the boss is male.

00:10:14.440 --> 00:10:21.440
[Guest 2]: And she said, I was immediately distrustful. And as it turned out later, there was no reason for her to feel that way.

00:10:21.440 --> 00:10:28.440
[Guest 2]: But that's how the alarms went up, because that's what had been conditioned into her after her time at Terry.

00:10:28.440 --> 00:10:37.440
[Guest 2]: And so much of it was so textbook. Right. So he would, you know, tell the women about how smart they were, how far he wanted to see them go.

00:10:37.440 --> 00:10:48.440
[Guest 2]: Then he would start talking to them about his marriage and there would be conversations about how it was failing, you know, how he really was not comfortable with the kind of equation he had with his wife.

00:10:48.440 --> 00:11:03.440
[Guest 2]: And it was a big decision for me to think over whether or not I wanted to put it into the story, because on some level, it does feel unfair to me that almost always we tend to put the spotlight on the women associated with men.

00:11:03.440 --> 00:11:12.440
[Guest 2]: Which is not to say that it's not justified, but sometimes we tend to put that spotlight more on the women than the accused themselves.

00:11:12.440 --> 00:11:30.440
[Guest 2]: But it seems so intrinsic to his modus operandi. And I remember reading his book, this terrible book called Return to Almora, which got really famous for its I mean, it was talked about a lot because it has a lot of very badly written sex scenes.

00:11:30.440 --> 00:11:39.440
[Guest 2]: But that part is actually the least interesting part of the book. I think he meant for it to be autobiographical, semi autobiographical in nature.

00:11:39.440 --> 00:11:56.440
[Guest 2]: That's the sense one gets as a reader. And there are parts of the book in which he's almost describing the modus operandi to you because there's an instance in which the protagonist, you know, fleeting love interest who makes an appearance in and out of the book has fallen in love with an older man.

00:11:56.440 --> 00:12:11.440
[Guest 2]: And there is an entire paragraph that I remember reading in which Pachori has written about how this older man had probably gotten her, you know, this naive young girl to fall for his advances because he gave her the same tired old story about a broken marriage.

00:12:11.440 --> 00:12:20.440
[Guest 2]: And at this point, I know what he's done with the survivors themselves. And I thought it was almost revoltingly self-aware, you know.

00:12:20.440 --> 00:12:31.440
[Guest 2]: And so there was that then he would isolate them. And that's, again, so dangerous because you're basically consciously cutting off channels for these women to reach out to.

00:12:31.440 --> 00:12:39.440
[Guest 2]: If I don't have colleagues, I can trust if I'm constantly being told that, you know, everyone out here is not looking for your well-being, but I am.

00:12:39.440 --> 00:12:55.440
[Guest 2]: You're also making sure that these women are going to ask themselves 10 times more whether or not they want to alienate the only supposed ally, who also happens to be the boss of this organization, who also happens to be the chair of the IPCC that has won a Nobel under him.

00:12:55.440 --> 00:13:03.440
[Guest 2]: Do I really want to cross paths with him? And maybe I'm getting this all wrong because, you know, he's been looking out for me this entire time.

00:13:03.440 --> 00:13:18.440
[Guest 2]: And that's when he would move into the territory of using this amplified vulnerability to justify his abhorrent actions, either the verbal comments he made or the kind of physical advances he thought it was kosher to make.

00:13:18.440 --> 00:13:25.440
[Guest 2]: By this time, even if the women are sure and they know what's happening, you're also aware of the power of this man.

00:13:25.440 --> 00:13:32.440
[Guest 2]: You've kind of seen it through the course of the grooming that he's put you through. In some cases, he would ask to meet their parents.

00:13:32.440 --> 00:13:41.440
[Guest 2]: You know, and one woman said that I was sure he did this to give me the sense that if I can't even talk to my parents, then, you know, where am I going to go?

00:13:41.440 --> 00:13:53.440
[Guest 2]: And that grooming is something that, you know, people who are child abusers do with children so that the children do not feel comfortable confiding in their parents about their experiences.

00:13:53.440 --> 00:14:06.440
[Guest 2]: And then, of course, there were the threats. There were decisions to take away work. There was the demeaning of the women's professional abilities, the objectification of them as women who invited this upon themselves.

00:14:06.440 --> 00:14:13.440
[Guest 2]: And this is, again, a really interesting defense that I see with especially men in positions of power who decide to sexually harass women.

00:14:13.440 --> 00:14:28.440
[Guest 2]: You made me do this. I can't take control of my feelings because you just, you know, you've, I, you kind of put the responsibility back on the woman for how she has filled you with passion that you didn't know existed.

00:14:28.440 --> 00:14:40.440
[Guest 2]: I mean, it's part of a template, but, you know, the women are made to feel like this is a unique case and somehow they are to blame for it because they're, you know, you were just so beautiful that I didn't know what else.

00:14:40.440 --> 00:14:51.440
[Guest 2]: Root has never happened to me before. And now, because these women are not speaking to each other, because that's the structure you've consciously created, in most cases, they're not even sure that this is a part of a template.

00:14:51.440 --> 00:14:57.440
[Guest 2]: Or even if they could have some idea, they don't know if they are going to be able to confirm that suspicion.

00:14:57.440 --> 00:15:11.440
[Guest 2]: And then also comes the part about, you know, playing up both what you could bring to their life, the havoc they are creating supposedly on your life and what you could do to them if they do decide to speak out.

00:15:11.440 --> 00:15:24.440
[Guest 2]: And this is said in insidious ways. Right. And the funniest part for me in a very bizarre way of all of this was that finally, after I was done reporting a few days before the story went to press, I did end up meeting Mr. Pachauri.

00:15:24.440 --> 00:15:30.440
[Guest 2]: And I felt like I was meeting someone I knew already, you know, because I'd just been thinking about him for so long.

00:15:30.440 --> 00:15:38.440
[Guest 2]: And there were things that I knew he did with other women that I saw him doing with me. And I was a journalist. He knew that he was talking to me on the record.

00:15:38.440 --> 00:15:46.440
[Guest 2]: I had a recorder switched on in his presence. And I remember that the minute I sat down and there was a photographer who was with me.

00:15:46.440 --> 00:15:56.440
[Guest 2]: He said, before we start the interview, can I just can I ask you something naughty? And I just thought that was fantastic, because how can you be so audacious?

00:15:56.440 --> 00:16:08.440
[Guest 2]: You know, I mean, and after which, for example, there were these things he would do. This was also a man who was obsessed with the idea of power, very much like a lot of men that we know in these positions.

00:16:08.440 --> 00:16:16.440
[Guest 2]: And one of the projections of that was to talk often about his cricketing prowess as a way to talk about his virility.

00:16:16.440 --> 00:16:27.440
[Guest 2]: Or he had this very strange habit of getting back toiletries from his trips abroad, which people in Delhi would go to collect, because that was the kind of cult he had created.

00:16:27.440 --> 00:16:31.440
[Guest 2]: During the interview, at some point, he did start talking about his cricketing ability.

00:16:31.440 --> 00:16:33.440
[Guest 2]: He didn't ask you any naughty questions?

00:16:33.440 --> 00:16:41.440
[Guest 2]: The naughty question was what Pranoy Roy's reaction to the NDTV story was, which I thought was quite boring. I mean, it was not naughty at all.

00:16:41.440 --> 00:16:42.440
[Guest 2]: You were disappointed?

00:16:42.440 --> 00:16:59.440
[Guest 2]: Yeah, I mean, I wasn't disappointed. I just thought that I'm talking to someone who really lacks in awareness about how they are to conduct themselves, considering he had a very, very public sexual harassment case being filed against him because of which he had lost professional opportunities.

00:16:59.440 --> 00:17:04.440
[Guest 1]: I don't know if it was the lack of self-awareness. It just sounds like a marvellous confidence.

00:17:04.440 --> 00:17:14.440
[Guest 2]: It is. It is. And I think just the idea that you can get away with this because you've been getting away with it for so long, you can't envisage a scenario within which you will not.

00:17:14.440 --> 00:17:23.440
[Guest 2]: I mean, think about it. Someone who's done this for 30 years. This is behaviour. I mean, this is your nature now. You don't know how else to be, I think.

00:17:23.440 --> 00:17:30.440
[Amit Varma]: And what I found as disturbing in your account as these patterns of behaviour is the fact of how other people looked upon them.

00:17:30.440 --> 00:17:36.440
[Amit Varma]: For example, you've quoted someone talking about him and talking about Mr. Pachauri and saying, oh, he's a man of colourful messages.

00:17:36.440 --> 00:17:47.440
[Amit Varma]: You know, and they'll talk about him affectionately and how he plays the field and he has a roving eye and all that, as if all of that is OK and it's standard and that's what you expect and kind of.

00:17:47.440 --> 00:17:56.440
[Amit Varma]: I imagine at some level, like what is disturbing is that these patterns of behaviour were probably known to a lot of his colleagues and they didn't find it wrong.

00:17:56.440 --> 00:18:03.440
[Amit Varma]: And perhaps therefore, he had the confidence to behave like that even when you went to interview him, because he didn't find it problematic either.

00:18:03.440 --> 00:18:14.440
[Guest 1]: I wonder if that's true of the reactions of a lot of men who are watching what is happening in these days and weeks and who sense that something big is going on,

00:18:14.440 --> 00:18:21.440
[Guest 1]: but aren't quite able to understand why, I think even more than the hashtag MeToo, why women are saying time's up.

00:18:21.440 --> 00:18:33.440
[Guest 1]: I don't think anybody gets that there's a ticking clock. And Amit, maybe you know something about this because you occupy spaces that Nikita and I, by virtue of our gender, don't necessarily do.

00:18:33.440 --> 00:18:42.440
[Guest 1]: And I really want to ask you and Nikita, I want to talk about what men are thinking at this time.

00:18:42.440 --> 00:18:49.440
[Amit Varma]: I think many men are shaken up, but most men are largely in denial. It's almost as if, hey, women are overreacting. What's the big deal?

00:18:49.440 --> 00:18:56.440
[Amit Varma]: And people will point out, again, a point that I'll bring up later about that, hey, there's a spectrum of abuse and some people are assaulters,

00:18:56.440 --> 00:19:03.440
[Amit Varma]: but a lot of these are bad dates or somebody cracking a bad joke on a date. And my point, and this is not a view I would have held, I think, 10 days ago.

00:19:03.440 --> 00:19:13.440
[Amit Varma]: But my point, I think one realization that I'm coming to is that this MeToo movement is not about the sexual assaults or crossing clear lines of consent.

00:19:13.440 --> 00:19:21.440
[Amit Varma]: Everyone agrees that is wrong. It's about patterns of sexism in our behavior, which are so normalized that we don't even know.

00:19:21.440 --> 00:19:27.440
[Amit Varma]: Like the classic example of that would be if you're in a mixed group, making jokes with sexual innovators, which are perfectly fine.

00:19:27.440 --> 00:19:33.440
[Amit Varma]: And then gaslighting the women if somebody protests and saying, oh, you know, you're too sensitive and all of that.

00:19:33.440 --> 00:19:41.440
[Amit Varma]: And one thing I realized, and I did an episode with the three of the women who work at Takshashila a couple of weeks back on the metrics of empowerment.

00:19:41.440 --> 00:19:49.440
[Amit Varma]: How can we figure out how women are getting empowered? And one revelation that kind of came up there was that every single moment of my life, my maleness doesn't matter to me.

00:19:49.440 --> 00:19:56.440
[Amit Varma]: I take my gender for granted. It is not a factor in how I interact with people. It's the exact other way around for women.

00:19:56.440 --> 00:20:02.440
[Amit Varma]: Every single moment of your time as a woman, your gender is a factor. You're getting onto a local train. You're getting into a restaurant.

00:20:02.440 --> 00:20:12.440
[Amit Varma]: You're talking with a man in a cafe. It is a factor. And therefore, this makes it imperative on men to make sure that they are cognizant of this.

00:20:12.440 --> 00:20:21.440
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, that they make that extra effort and apply that filter to make sure that women are not uncomfortable in any way in their presence,

00:20:21.440 --> 00:20:30.440
[Amit Varma]: which could be something as simple as making sure that you change the kind of humor that you do in mixed company, which could be something as sort of simple.

00:20:30.440 --> 00:20:35.440
[Amit Varma]: Let's say, for example, you know, as a middle aged man, I grew up in the 80s and the 90s and all of that.

00:20:35.440 --> 00:20:42.440
[Amit Varma]: And the norms of how you greet women have changed. Earlier, you would just nod or some circles to a namaste, then you shook hands.

00:20:42.440 --> 00:20:50.440
[Amit Varma]: Now you hug and all of that, which I found very awkward to navigate. So the best solution, I think, for any man in that case is if you're meeting a woman in a social setting,

00:20:50.440 --> 00:20:57.440
[Amit Varma]: just let her make the first move. You know, just go with that. Just I mean, this sounds very sort of masculine.

00:20:57.440 --> 00:21:08.440
[Amit Varma]: But think of it as a game theory problem that I will optimize my behavior in such a way that the chance of the woman feeling uncomfortable is minimized.

00:21:08.440 --> 00:21:16.440
[Amit Varma]: And this is something that I don't think men get that they behave in ways they think are normal and they don't understand the reactions of women.

00:21:16.440 --> 00:21:23.440
[Guest 1]: I don't think game theory is masculine. I mean, I know that.

00:21:23.440 --> 00:21:30.440
[Guest 1]: I'm also sorry. I also noticed that even though I met and I have known each other for years today, he waited for me to hug him.

00:21:30.440 --> 00:21:34.440
[Unknown]: I appreciate that. And I also appreciate what you're saying.

00:21:34.440 --> 00:21:44.440
[Guest 1]: I realize that behavioral boundaries change and that it's as difficult for men to navigate as women in many ways.

00:21:44.440 --> 00:21:57.440
[Guest 1]: But one of the things I think many of us have realized or under underscored for ourselves in the last few days is that women have to bear the brunt of that to an unimaginable extent.

00:21:57.440 --> 00:22:09.440
[Guest 1]: And one of the things that frustrates me is that the sort of radical empathy that this confessions and this discourse is generating among women for each other doesn't seem to have reached men.

00:22:09.440 --> 00:22:25.440
[Guest 1]: And I feel like the onus is on on men to if you if you can't feel our pain, quote unquote, at least recognize that what your discomfort is and do something productive with it instead of brushing it under the carpet and waiting for all of this to go away.

00:22:25.440 --> 00:22:32.440
[Amit Varma]: And that's doubly ironic, because in the world that we are in, it's the unfortunate fact that men make more of a difference to these things than women do.

00:22:32.440 --> 00:22:40.440
[Amit Varma]: So it's incumbent on men to speak up, which is therefore the dilemma I also face. You know, I was asked to write a piece about this for the Hindu, which I'll probably write tomorrow.

00:22:40.440 --> 00:22:50.440
[Amit Varma]: And the dilemma I face is that men speaking out the danger you're in is you could be virtue signaling, which we see a lot of, or you could be making it about yourself suddenly, which again, men tend to do.

00:22:50.440 --> 00:22:58.440
[Amit Varma]: But it is about men. Yeah, but you know, in a different way, as if you're showing how compassionate you are and how enlightened you are and so on.

00:22:58.440 --> 00:23:04.440
[Amit Varma]: And that's a danger you face. But at the same time, it's it's the men also have to speak up. And I think a few have,

00:23:04.440 --> 00:23:23.440
[Guest 2]: I think one of the conversations that I'd like to hear from men instead of, you know, for example, when the entire thing had started, and it started with someone from the comedy circuit sort of being, you know, held accountable for a lot of his harassment.

00:23:23.440 --> 00:23:30.440
[Guest 2]: What I would have liked to really hear is from other comedians exactly how they thought they were complicit.

00:23:30.440 --> 00:23:40.440
[Guest 2]: And I think one of the issues with men when they do decide to speak about this is that we don't hear often enough of how they are holding themselves accountable.

00:23:40.440 --> 00:23:54.440
[Guest 2]: And even now, I feel like I see a lot of women doing this introspection, you know, the ways in which we have enabled environments that we feel unsafe in enabled men who we are now recognizing have done many problematic things.

00:23:54.440 --> 00:24:06.440
[Guest 2]: And what is it that we need to change to make this better? Because really, what something like this is asking of all of us is to be better people is to be more kind, more compassionate, more considerate.

00:24:06.440 --> 00:24:14.440
[Guest 2]: And that kind of goes against everything that we've been, you know, societally or individually conditioned with.

00:24:14.440 --> 00:24:31.440
[Guest 2]: And I think that that's incumbent on both men and women. But even now, along with the kind of trauma that reliving this kind of abuse brings with it and reading stories of it brings with it, I still see more women at least thinking out loud about the ways in which they could have contributed.

00:24:31.440 --> 00:24:45.440
[Guest 2]: And I feel like most of the men I am hearing from are either completely detached in the way that they're saying that we see that this is happening to you, whereas this is happening to all of us, you know, when creating safer environments for all of us.

00:24:45.440 --> 00:24:50.440
[Guest 1]: I really felt the truth of what you tweeted yesterday. Could you repeat it?

00:24:50.440 --> 00:25:01.440
[Guest 2]: I think it was something on the lines of, you know, women are going about their daily jobs, they're grappling with anxiety and guilt, they're collating these lists, they're responding to legitimate criticisms of what's happening.

00:25:01.440 --> 00:25:10.440
[Guest 2]: And on top of this, they're all checking in on each other, you know, like, I think I've spoken to more women in the past four or five days than I had in months.

00:25:10.440 --> 00:25:20.440
[Guest 2]: And I love it because they're all constantly checking in on whether you've eaten, have you had enough water? Are you getting enough rest? Are you taking care of yourself? Switch off when you need to.

00:25:20.440 --> 00:25:28.440
[Guest 2]: And I had a conversation with Supriya right after I came to Bombay. And it was the first time I was actually speaking to someone about what had happened because I'd been traveling for work.

00:25:28.440 --> 00:25:40.440
[Guest 2]: And I just felt such a great amount of comfort. And from men, I just want so much as a, you know, how are you doing? I hope you're okay. And I'm not even hearing that much.

00:25:40.440 --> 00:25:44.440
[Guest 2]: And that for me personally is really frustrating.

00:25:44.440 --> 00:25:52.440
[Guest 1]: I respect the silence of a lot of men I know who may be thinking about this deeply, or who may feel uncomfortable or feel like it's not their place.

00:25:52.440 --> 00:25:58.440
[Guest 1]: And I get why men feel like it's not their place to intrude on a conversation that women are having.

00:25:58.440 --> 00:26:06.440
[Guest 1]: But without pointing fingers, I also want to say that there is a certain kind of silence that is a complicity of its own.

00:26:06.440 --> 00:26:22.440
[Guest 1]: And if it's the silence that means that you're waiting for something to blow over, or that means that you can't condemn obviously unsavory behavior or that you can't condemn misconduct, because you're thinking back to something you've done yourself.

00:26:22.440 --> 00:26:31.440
[Guest 1]: And thinking, oh boy, now I really can't say I'm sorry about this, because this is how I behave too. Then, then you know, there's work to be done over there as well.

00:26:31.440 --> 00:26:38.440
[Amit Varma]: But going back to what Nikita said about women talking more to each other, and you know, that kind of shared.

00:26:38.440 --> 00:26:47.440
[Amit Varma]: Is this in that sense, a watershed moment in the sense that earlier if something happened, a woman felt she had no choice but to keep quiet, let it pass, get over it, move on to the next moment.

00:26:47.440 --> 00:26:54.440
[Amit Varma]: But now they feel the solidarity and because other people are speaking up, they feel that they can speak up as well.

00:26:54.440 --> 00:27:03.440
[Amit Varma]: Only if the, you know, one person accuses man X, nine other people will feel emboldened by that and come out. And is that happening?

00:27:03.440 --> 00:27:11.440
[Guest 1]: I think one way I would qualify that is that the number of women involved in this conversation is still very small, and that it's very stratified.

00:27:11.440 --> 00:27:26.440
[Guest 1]: We know that there are women in smaller towns who speak languages that aren't English, who aren't upper caste or upper class, have constraints that are unimaginable to those of us who are speaking up or participating, or even just reaching out to each other.

00:27:26.440 --> 00:27:35.440
[Guest 1]: To the second part of your question, I'm, because there's more data out in the environment now, I think we can say that the conversation has broadened.

00:27:35.440 --> 00:27:45.440
[Guest 1]: I don't know if this is wholesale different from how women spoke to each other. The phrase the whisper network has come up very often in the last few days.

00:27:45.440 --> 00:27:57.440
[Guest 1]: And that hints at this sort of unstructured, private way in which women spoke to each other, warned each other of men or institutions that they knew to be problematic.

00:27:57.440 --> 00:28:06.440
[Guest 1]: What I think has changed, though, is a new awareness of a pattern. And I think an underlining of the fact that none of what happened to us or our friends was okay.

00:28:06.440 --> 00:28:14.440
[Guest 1]: I can't tell you the number of times I have seen a story about a prominent man come out on Twitter and think, holy crap.

00:28:14.440 --> 00:28:23.440
[Guest 1]: My friend told me the same thing about the same man, except that instead of happening to her at a conference in Goa, it happened at a party in Delhi. So this is a pattern of misbehavior.

00:28:23.440 --> 00:28:33.440
[Guest 1]: The difference is that when my friend told me the same story, I felt bad for her. I filed it away as a black mark against the man in question, and I moved on.

00:28:33.440 --> 00:28:45.440
[Guest 1]: And now I realize that that it was far from an isolated incident. And the patterns are becoming really clear to me. And that, I think, shows me about the breadth of the problem.

00:28:45.440 --> 00:28:53.440
[Amit Varma]: In fact, before you guys got here, my producer Swati was telling me about how there haven't been any me too from Hindi journalism or language journalism.

00:28:53.440 --> 00:29:10.440
[Guest 2]: I think there are some regional journalists who are coming out. And I think Supriya Sharma had a fairly interesting sort of insight on this, which is that the kind of concerns that women in English language media were facing, you know, a few decades ago.

00:29:10.440 --> 00:29:22.440
[Guest 2]: There are a lot of journalists in smaller cities and towns who are still facing those concerns. And I think, like Supriya was pointing out, I think, I don't know if this is a watershed moment.

00:29:22.440 --> 00:29:36.440
[Guest 2]: I think this was something that has been in the making for many months, if not years now. So, for example, even the idea of naming predators first came with Losha, the list that Raya kind of collated.

00:29:36.440 --> 00:29:51.440
[Guest 2]: Should we introduce that list? Yeah, sorry. So there was basically Raya Sarkar, who at that time, I think, was a law student, had put together a list of men in academia who are known to be predators based on complaints that she was receiving.

00:29:51.440 --> 00:30:04.440
[Guest 2]: And at that time, the list had generated a lot of controversy. And that's why I think there is a need to introspect on how we look at this particular moment as being unique, because I'm not sure that it's unique.

00:30:04.440 --> 00:30:22.440
[Guest 2]: I think it's broadened the scope in terms of the conversations that are happening. But even that broadening should be, I mean, we should look at that broadening with some amount of skepticism, because I think what had happened at that time was not very different from what is happening now in the methodology.

00:30:22.440 --> 00:30:40.440
[Guest 2]: I mean, here also, there are women who are either choosing to put out their complaints or to navigate their complaints through women they trust. And there are a number of women on Twitter who are doing the very hard work of kind of keeping track of complaints and putting them out where the complainants want anonymity.

00:30:40.440 --> 00:30:56.440
[Guest 2]: Raya was doing that as one person. Now, neither of these, as I think Makepeace was pointing out on Twitter, neither of these can claim to be perfect. But they were in themselves movements that tell you about how broken the system is. There is a statement about that as well.

00:30:56.440 --> 00:31:17.440
[Guest 2]: And so I feel like Raya kind of set that in motion. And so, for example, even the radical sort of empathy that we were discussing, unfortunately, at that time, we didn't see. And so clearly, there's also still a lot of work for this very, if you would call it a movement or this very space to do in terms of also becoming more inclusive.

00:31:17.440 --> 00:31:35.440
[Guest 1]: Can I ask something? I've been wondering, there are many obvious reasons for why the list of shame as Raya Sarkar's list, which came out last year, was called, got less sympathy and less attention than the current wave of accusations.

00:31:35.440 --> 00:31:50.440
[Guest 1]: I've been trying to think of why. One of the reasons, as many people have pointed out, is that the degree of anonymity of the accusers in that case was somewhat deeper.

00:31:50.440 --> 00:32:08.440
[Guest 1]: Many of the accusers were not only anonymous, but they were also coming from positions of marginality. They were juniors in academia. They were students. They were women who were entirely dependent on men and on institutional power for the jobs and the work that they were doing.

00:32:08.440 --> 00:32:23.440
[Guest 1]: Many people have pointed out that because Raya Sarkar is Dalit, there's an element of marginality and a lack of sympathy from upper caste women that's kind of hard coded into how they approach anything she did or said.

00:32:23.440 --> 00:32:38.440
[Guest 1]: One of the details that I've been focused on is also that, however, is also the fact that the accused in this round of allegations are just higher profile.

00:32:38.440 --> 00:32:54.440
[Guest 1]: And because they're involved in the media and in the creative industries, and because there's a degree of celebrity involved there that, you know, Partha Chatterjee doesn't have for all his fame, this kind of becomes headline news in a way that the list of shame didn't.

00:32:54.440 --> 00:33:00.440
[Guest 1]: I'm not trying to find excuses for why we're reacting now differently from the way we reacted then.

00:33:00.440 --> 00:33:15.440
[Amit Varma]: I have an observation slash follow up question to that. I mean, one reason could, of course, be just the nature of the industries that was academia versus media. But one thing that has struck me now is that one of the things that drove the anger then from all of these women were that due process isn't working.

00:33:15.440 --> 00:33:31.440
[Amit Varma]: That's why we have to do this. And one of the things I've noticed about this current thing, what has happened over the last week is that we actually see due process working in some cases. I don't know whether it's as a consequence of that, but Business Standard fired one reporter, Hindustan Times made the political editor step down.

00:33:31.440 --> 00:33:45.440
[Amit Varma]: All India Bakchod has been cancelled by Hotstar. You know, Mami pulled films by Rajat Kapoor from their list. And I know of various other organizations which are taking this kind of action fairly seriously and not as tokenism.

00:33:45.440 --> 00:34:09.440
[Guest 2]: But that's actually not necessarily due process, right? Because the I think, in fact, the response to these accusations versus the accusations that came earlier is on the institutions. There was no reason for institutions to not put in place due process. Then it was just easier because the debate became fractured in a way that it became easy to delegitimize Raya's efforts.

00:34:09.440 --> 00:34:22.440
[Guest 2]: And I think it's also important to remember that at that point, this was one woman who was also being blamed for all sorts of bizarre things like creating a void within feminists in India, etc., which I personally found rather strange.

00:34:22.440 --> 00:34:43.440
[Guest 2]: And Lawrence Liang, for example, there was actually due process that got put in. And that's the one name I remember. I think there were at least there were multiple men that I remember in some institutions either did take action. Sadanand Menon, for example, is a very good example of someone who was on that list.

00:34:43.440 --> 00:35:03.440
[Guest 2]: The Institute did not take any action. And finally, a survivor also who had, I think, contributed to the list decided to come out. And now we know that due process hasn't worked. But I don't know if that's on the list itself or on the institutions and the way in which they chose to react then versus the way in which they are choosing to react now.

00:35:03.440 --> 00:35:18.440
[Guest 2]: Because even the scale of this is defined by our ready acceptance of this wave of allegations versus the list then. And I think that's as much on us and the institutions more than, you know, just the people who are spearheading the efforts.

00:35:18.440 --> 00:35:36.440
[Guest 2]: And of course, I think there have also, I mean, we are now like we were discussing in day six. And, you know, there's also been, for some reason, because of the kind of momentum that has been driven by, for example, institutions taking action or the fact that these are journalists we've read or heard about.

00:35:36.440 --> 00:36:03.440
[Guest 2]: And also Tanushree Dutta, I think, who kind of also set things in motion by talking about her experiences with Nana Patekar. It has continued for longer. I'm just not sure if it's the nature of the original efforts themselves or also some of our own prejudices that caused one effort to, you know, really catch momentum while another just sort of got sidelined by all the criticism that was lobbed at it.

00:36:03.440 --> 00:36:21.440
[Guest 1]: I think it's absolutely clear that the failure of due process was what instigated the list of shame in the first place. And I think most universities, with some exceptions, behaved shamefully in light of those accusations, refusing to treat them as forget about delegitimizing them.

00:36:21.440 --> 00:36:46.440
[Guest 1]: They, you know, they ignored them. They called them ill-informed and vague. I'm quoting exactly from what ACJ said in the case of Sadanand Menon, who was adjunct faculty over there at the time and who not only got the support of his institute, but also of a lot of other influential women, including feminists, who put out a letter saying that, oh, you know, we should be more responsible about these sort of accusations.

00:36:46.440 --> 00:37:02.440
[Guest 1]: Well, yes, there is an infrastructure of responsibility, but it was entirely on the institutions who abdicated their role in that responsibility and forced young women to lash out, if you like, in the way they did.

00:37:02.440 --> 00:37:21.440
[Guest 1]: Raya and I think her, you know, people who supported her said very clearly that, look, whatever happens, I mean, they were like, look, we're tired. And you should know that if you're entering the halls of academia, that if this guy is like has you on his radar, it's a problem for you.

00:37:21.440 --> 00:37:37.440
[Guest 1]: And I, you know, I respect that. I recognize, of course, that there's potential for abuse. And so did everybody involved. But the MeToo movement from the very beginning, I think, over the last year, ever since the Weinstein story came out, has been anarchic in nature.

00:37:37.440 --> 00:37:55.440
[Guest 1]: And we've had to take it and roll with it. And for all those who are worried about false accusations, particularly as far as academia were concerned. And I have to say this for those who are worried about false accusations against male academics, like this was your chance to make due process work.

00:37:55.440 --> 00:38:15.440
[Guest 1]: If you were worried that the women had violated some kind of boundary, why didn't you let your institutional mechanisms do the work of clearing the names of the men you were concerned about? Very few people did that. And I mean, look, as a result, what we have now is men like Sadanand Menon named on a second list now with multiple accusations of misconduct against him.

00:38:15.440 --> 00:38:29.440
[Guest 1]: And, you know, I'm not sure. I feel like our focus should be on the abusers. But I also want to ask the women who publicly backed him to think about what they did and how they hampered the cause of justice.

00:38:29.440 --> 00:38:36.440
[Guest 2]: Sorry, I just realized that we misgendered Raya because their preferred pronouns are there in them.

00:38:36.440 --> 00:38:41.440
[Guest 1]: Oh, sorry. So apologies for that on behalf of all of us. I'm really sorry. I didn't know that.

