00:39:58.440 --> 00:40:05.440
[Amit Varma]: One of the issues that you brought up yourself with regard to the last list by Raya Sarkar was that more of those complaints were anonymous.

00:40:05.440 --> 00:40:11.440
[Amit Varma]: And that's an objection that people have been raising even now that, you know, what do you do about anonymous complaints?

00:40:11.440 --> 00:40:13.440
[Amit Varma]: Anybody can make up anything and put it out there.

00:40:13.440 --> 00:40:18.440
[Guest 1]: I know that both that list and this current wave of allegations seems chaotic.

00:40:18.440 --> 00:40:23.440
[Guest 1]: But actually, if you think about it, it's there is a structure to it.

00:40:23.440 --> 00:40:31.440
[Guest 1]: In the last list, Raya, tremendous risk to themselves, became the conduit and the curator of these accusations.

00:40:31.440 --> 00:40:41.440
[Guest 1]: So because they were assuring you that they knew the identity of the accuser, they were in some sense doing what we do in formal institutional settings as well,

00:40:41.440 --> 00:40:47.440
[Guest 1]: which is to protect the identity of an accuser in a complaint involving rape or sexual harassment.

00:40:47.440 --> 00:40:58.440
[Guest 1]: In this case, we have two or three women on Twitter who through whom these complaints are being aired anonymously when they are anonymous.

00:40:58.440 --> 00:41:08.440
[Guest 1]: And I think the discourse has pretty quickly picked up and sensitized itself to good faith in all of these cases.

00:41:08.440 --> 00:41:14.440
[Guest 1]: There are reasons for them to trust the women who are putting out these anonymous accounts.

00:41:14.440 --> 00:41:24.440
[Guest 1]: And I feel like while we're still evolving our sense of objectivity in these cases, it's not entirely absent.

00:41:24.440 --> 00:41:29.440
[Amit Varma]: In fact, it's almost happened in real time in the sense that, you know, we've seen some of the fake allegations happening,

00:41:29.440 --> 00:41:33.440
[Amit Varma]: but also the ecosystem has evolved just within the last six days.

00:41:33.440 --> 00:41:41.440
[Amit Varma]: And I also know that, OK, if I see like Ritu Ponna's account at Masala Bhai or Sandhya Menon's, I know I can trust them that they're verifying this themselves.

00:41:41.440 --> 00:41:47.440
[Amit Varma]: So even if they put out something which is anonymous, they have in some way given it credibility and verified it.

00:41:47.440 --> 00:41:49.440
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, you can kind of trust those accounts.

00:41:49.440 --> 00:41:52.440
[Guest 2]: I mean, which I think was very much the case with Raya's list as well,

00:41:52.440 --> 00:42:00.440
[Guest 2]: because they were also doing very much the same work that I imagine people who are putting out complaints on Twitter right now are.

00:42:00.440 --> 00:42:01.440
[Guest 2]: And I also, sorry.

00:42:01.440 --> 00:42:10.440
[Guest 1]: I think the one thing that this round of allegations has that the List of Shame didn't though is the abundance of screenshots.

00:42:10.440 --> 00:42:15.440
[Guest 1]: So the sense that you have something that's not just a name on an Excel sheet,

00:42:15.440 --> 00:42:23.440
[Guest 1]: but also a story that you can see that someone has DMed this person that offers you details, that offers you texture.

00:42:23.440 --> 00:42:28.440
[Guest 1]: I feel like psychologically that's made a difference to readers.

00:42:28.440 --> 00:42:34.440
[Amit Varma]: But does it worry you that people could jump on this bandwagon like over the weekend, for example, starting Sunday night?

00:42:34.440 --> 00:42:44.440
[Amit Varma]: You had a flurry of clearly fake accounts by clear sock puppet handles, which were run by somebody's IT cell, which were easily rebutted.

00:42:44.440 --> 00:42:49.440
[Amit Varma]: But nevertheless, there is a worry that then people jump on the bandwagon, use a MeToo hashtag, make up anything they want.

00:42:49.440 --> 00:42:50.440
[Amit Varma]: How do you deal with that?

00:42:50.440 --> 00:42:56.440
[Guest 1]: I'm waiting to see how the element of fake news evolves in this case.

00:42:56.440 --> 00:43:05.440
[Guest 1]: What you've described right now, because it's so clearly easily rebutted, makes it clear that just pulling up a couple of sock puppet accounts

00:43:05.440 --> 00:43:11.440
[Guest 1]: and deciding to point fingers at someone because you don't like them isn't necessarily going to work.

00:43:11.440 --> 00:43:15.440
[Guest 1]: Public trust is more nuanced than that.

00:43:15.440 --> 00:43:31.440
[Guest 1]: But I'm interested to think about what the future might hold, though, and how as this conversation evolves, the sophistication of threats against people against whom someone might have an agenda also evolves.

00:43:31.440 --> 00:43:38.440
[Guest 2]: Also, I feel like we've kind of been through these concerns again, just to go back to the list.

00:43:38.440 --> 00:43:41.440
[Guest 2]: Also, is it the list of sexual harassers in academia or list of shame?

00:43:41.440 --> 00:43:45.440
[Unknown]: Oh, sorry, I know it is the list of shame.

00:43:45.440 --> 00:43:46.440
[Amit Varma]: What's the distinction?

00:43:46.440 --> 00:43:50.440
[Guest 1]: I mean, it's the same acronym. I just am wondering what the full form is.

00:43:50.440 --> 00:43:54.440
[Guest 1]: It's called, yeah, it's called hashtag low sharp when people talk about it amongst themselves.

00:43:54.440 --> 00:44:06.440
[Guest 2]: So but I thought even with the list, for example, a lot of people at that time, for various reasons, known to them were saying that we don't know if these complaints are actually legitimate because they're anonymized.

00:44:06.440 --> 00:44:14.440
[Guest 2]: And at that time, I remember that I knew some people who were far more well versed with the world of academia than I was.

00:44:14.440 --> 00:44:18.440
[Guest 2]: And you'd come back and you'd say, oh, OK, this person is on the list, too.

00:44:18.440 --> 00:44:20.440
[Guest 2]: And it's of course, we've heard stories about them.

00:44:20.440 --> 00:44:48.440
[Guest 2]: And even in this round, like Supriya was pointing out, I feel like at least up until now, of course, it's shocking the spectrum of men who seem to have harmed women. But I haven't seen anything that would worry me in terms of being if it were a fake allegation that to me has matched up to, you know, the hype threads that we hear about destruction of reputations or.

00:44:48.440 --> 00:44:52.440
[Guest 1]: I mean, I think we should prepare for efforts like that. I'm just not sure what those efforts would look like.

00:44:52.440 --> 00:45:06.440
[Guest 1]: And but maybe there's someone sitting somewhere in some IT cell frantically thinking up ways to get me to believe allegations against against a person I would otherwise rather trust.

00:45:06.440 --> 00:45:09.440
[Guest 1]: But it seems like a bit of a long shot at this point.

00:45:09.440 --> 00:45:24.440
[Amit Varma]: And a friend of mine, whom I won't name because I haven't taken her permission, obviously, but she's an editor in a major newspaper, told me recently that when the low chalice came out, she was against it because she was worried about due process and presumption of innocence and all of those factors.

00:45:24.440 --> 00:45:29.440
[Amit Varma]: But now she is saying she's changed her mind. Now she's saying, let there be collateral damage. This needs to happen.

00:45:29.440 --> 00:45:34.440
[Amit Varma]: And I kind of agree with her. But what do you guys feel about that? What is the factor of collateral damage?

00:45:34.440 --> 00:45:36.440
[Amit Varma]: Which is, of course, is something that men will stress on.

00:45:36.440 --> 00:45:46.440
[Guest 1]: Yeah. An overstate, in my opinion. I think the problems remain with or without collateral damage because they're essentially moral.

00:45:46.440 --> 00:46:00.440
[Guest 1]: So if you do worry about, for example, the presumption of innocence and you believe that the same principle that applies in a courtroom should apply in how we relate to each other in public life, then that problem doesn't necessarily go away.

00:46:00.440 --> 00:46:15.440
[Guest 1]: And I don't think these allegations or the previous ones change that. But if you look at this as an opportunity to think about drawing distinctions between how institutions can and should process complaints.

00:46:15.440 --> 00:46:31.440
[Guest 1]: The reforms that we want to make in culture and society simply by airing out these problems, acknowledging that they're problems and, you know, and discomforting some individuals in the process, then you should see these as a good thing.

00:46:31.440 --> 00:46:47.440
[Guest 1]: I agree that it seems unfair. And I'm thinking right now, particularly of a friend of mine who was not accused of abuse, but who admitted to complicity in covering up an episode of abuse and has taken the hit for it professionally.

00:46:47.440 --> 00:47:01.440
[Guest 1]: While I have some sympathy for the fact that this one man has suffered for doing something that many men have done, I also recognize that that's where change begins.

00:47:01.440 --> 00:47:18.440
[Guest 1]: And because of one person taking the hit, as I said, if it allows more people to introspect about their own behavior and to not make the same mistakes, then I'm prepared for that. You know, I mean, women have been taking hits for a very long time.

00:47:18.440 --> 00:47:38.440
[Guest 2]: Sorry, just to jump in, but that last part to me is also something that I'm very curious about, because one of the things that I've noticed tends to happen with the discourse is that we are still centering the men, you know, the men who are going to be affected by the allegations made against them, what kind of apologies they're putting out.

00:47:38.440 --> 00:47:55.440
[Guest 2]: And I wonder what it would look like to center what the women have lost, because I fear that the scale of that is so large that it's difficult to talk about what would reparations look like, for example, which is something I think that Rega also pointed out.

00:47:55.440 --> 00:48:18.440
[Guest 2]: But it's something that I am deeply interested in, because I do think that what happens is that in these cases, I mean, you're talking about such a large volume of women who have been affected professionally, personally, mentally, emotionally, physically, that we can't, it's difficult for us to fathom what it would look like to start talking about what we do for those women.

00:48:18.440 --> 00:48:36.440
[Guest 2]: I mean, what does justice or what does some form of justice look like when you've suffered that much? And one of the interesting aspects to what we were beginning to talk about was men and what happens with collateral damage for men, which I think I'm kind of on board with what Supriya is saying.

00:48:36.440 --> 00:48:48.440
[Guest 2]: But for me, I wonder when we can reach a point where we can start talking about what happens to the women who've come out and spoken. I mean, how do we make up for all the lost time?

00:48:48.440 --> 00:49:09.440
[Amit Varma]: People talk about the careers of these accused people getting ruined. But what about the women like, you know, Vintananda, for example, whose career ended 19 years ago? And, you know, and how can you then show? I mean, one of the interesting things about this MeToo movement, and maybe I'm being too optimistic about this, but where I think it will work and where I think it will not work. Why are you laughing?

00:49:09.440 --> 00:49:27.440
[Amit Varma]: I'm cynical about I'm cynical that is necessarily going to get women justice for what has happened in the past, or that all of the people who have been predators or who have been complicit will be brought brought to account.

00:49:27.440 --> 00:49:41.440
[Amit Varma]: What I am optimistic about is that it will change the culture in the future in just something as simple as even if men don't change the way they feel internally, it changes the incentives for their behavior.

00:49:41.440 --> 00:49:58.440
[Amit Varma]: So now the next time you are, you know, on a date pushing past someone after they say no for the first time, or the next time you're cracking an inappropriate joke or putting your hand on someone's thigh, you're going to think twice. Earlier you could get away with impunity because you were, you know, you were just being friendly.

00:49:58.440 --> 00:50:15.440
[Amit Varma]: And I really do think that's going to change. I think men have to think twice, even if they're thinking twice for the wrong reasons. Hey, what if I get exposed? Even if they're doing it for the wrong reasons, some of that behavior will surely change. Don't you think so?

00:50:15.440 --> 00:50:36.440
[Guest 1]: I also think that the behavior of women will change because now, when someone puts their hand on your thigh, instead of normalizing it and keeping your keeping how shaken you feel or how bad you feel about it to yourself, you hopefully you'll now think, but he's not allowed to do that and react and react quicker.

00:50:36.440 --> 00:50:49.440
[Guest 1]: And hopefully some of the stories that have taken 20 years to come out won't take 20 years to come out after this. I, I, well, I'm a pessimist of the intellect in this case, but an optimist of the will, to quote Gramsci.

00:50:49.440 --> 00:51:09.440
[Guest 1]: One of the things that Nikita's excellent story, I think, crystallizes that is the truth about this culture is that that hashtag times up isn't so much a warning to men as I think it is a call to women.

00:51:09.440 --> 00:51:22.440
[Guest 1]: And it's not a call to say that an era has ended, but that our work has just begun and the fight is going to be endless. You only have to read the Pachauri story to realize just why.

00:51:22.440 --> 00:51:28.440
[Guest 1]: But hopefully this means more women realize that they have fellow combatants and they're not alone.

00:51:28.440 --> 00:51:47.440
[Guest 2]: My worry would just be that, are we also going to see more people calling out problematic behavior that they've witnessed? Because I think the role of a witness in these cases, and it doesn't necessarily have to be an act of physical transgression that you view, but like we were talking about the culture of an office, for example.

00:51:47.440 --> 00:52:01.440
[Guest 2]: We haven't even gotten into conversations about gender discrimination with journalism, for example, the different kinds of stories and this, I would like to believe is less true today than it was, say, 10 years ago.

00:52:01.440 --> 00:52:14.440
[Guest 2]: But it is still very much a part of the truth, which is the kind of beats that one tends to assign women to or the kind of very masculine understanding we have of being on the field.

00:52:14.440 --> 00:52:28.440
[Guest 2]: We haven't even begun to get into those conversations. But even before that, if we are to talk about a culture that's changing and we have to talk about women who feel more empowered to articulate the kind of discomfort we know we've been having for years.

00:52:28.440 --> 00:52:39.440
[Guest 2]: I'm also hoping it means that we're able to help others articulate that discomfort as well, because I think a large part of this silence is that we're told silence is status quo.

00:52:39.440 --> 00:52:48.440
[Guest 2]: So doing something other than status quo feels strange. So, for example, if Pachauri was picking women up on their birthdays, that was something that everyone could see.

00:52:48.440 --> 00:52:55.440
[Guest 2]: And if no one spoke up, then I would think that real change would begin when they start recognizing that as problematic.

00:52:55.440 --> 00:53:10.440
[Guest 2]: Or, for example, if there was a man who I knew was very supportive of the complainant, but then started complaining to me about how he could not understand the women not speaking up about Pachauri because, and I remember this verbatim, that men have families to look after.

00:53:10.440 --> 00:53:15.440
[Guest 2]: So I get that they're worried about their jobs, but these women, they're just doing the job to buy makeup.

00:53:15.440 --> 00:53:32.440
[Guest 2]: And the thought was quite violent from someone who was actually supporting a survivor of sexual harassment. And I hope that along with behavior, the idea that this is a problem for women to deal with also changes, because it's a problem for all of us to deal with.

00:53:32.440 --> 00:53:45.440
[Guest 2]: And it cannot be the onus of just, you know, the people from across various sections who are oppressed trying to make it better, because I don't think the work will get done then.

00:53:45.440 --> 00:54:03.440
[Guest 1]: Yeah, I think it's significant that in many of the industries where names have been named so far, there's a sense that a kind of open informality, a liberal workplace culture makes a place more humane. It makes it more personal. It allows for creative freedom of some sort.

00:54:03.440 --> 00:54:24.440
[Guest 1]: When in fact, all of these are encoded in patterns of domination that are very, very harmful to the people being dominated, most often women, we know that sexual harassment is actually a tool of that inequality, that it's normalized to such a degree that as much as paying women less or keeping them from promotions,

00:54:24.440 --> 00:54:33.440
[Guest 1]: just the simple act of humiliating them in a million different ways, you know, allows you to exploit their labor or exploit them as laborers.

00:54:33.440 --> 00:54:46.440
[Guest 1]: So if people are saying that, oh, this is going to end all kinds of human and personal interaction and it's not going to be the same and, you know, feminism is going to like segregate us by gender again,

00:54:46.440 --> 00:54:56.440
[Guest 1]: or even do the things you mentioned, which is to think twice about the kind of jokes that you're cracking in mixed company, which people will say, oh, that sounds so Edwardian, we used to do that like 100 years ago.

00:54:56.440 --> 00:55:07.440
[Guest 1]: You want to send us back to the past? Well, no, not necessarily. But the way to think about it is that if this ushers in a new era of more formal workplace relations,

00:55:07.440 --> 00:55:19.440
[Guest 1]: then our worry should not be that those formalities will constrain us. We should be happy that they will hopefully stamp out a kind of inequality that we have refused to acknowledge all this while,

00:55:19.440 --> 00:55:24.440
[Guest 1]: and that they in turn will lead to new kinds of equality, which leads to new kinds of freedom.

00:55:24.440 --> 00:55:31.440
[Amit Varma]: And I'd say that liberate us not constrain us. And also men also diminish themselves, you know, by being complicit in this.

00:55:31.440 --> 00:55:38.440
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, and I'd urge all my listeners to just pick up the phone and look at whatever family WhatsApp groups they have.

00:55:38.440 --> 00:55:48.440
[Amit Varma]: And look at the last 20 memes or jokes that have been sent there. And tell me how many of them you feel you should object to, but actually don't because hey, you know, why stir up the waters.

00:55:48.440 --> 00:56:03.440
[Guest 2]: And I mean, once you get into family systems, you're just talking a different kind of, I think, you know, scale of harassment altogether. Because I was talking about this with one of the women journalists

00:56:03.440 --> 00:56:12.440
[Guest 2]: who has also been following what's happening online. And we were just talking about how all of us know or have experienced some discomfort at the hands of a male relative,

00:56:12.440 --> 00:56:23.440
[Guest 2]: or, you know, child abuse, which kind of usually we don't talk about, especially if it comes out from extended family members, which is shockingly common.

00:56:23.440 --> 00:56:30.440
[Guest 2]: And, sorry to come back to the parallels with the Pachauri story, but I remember one of the things that I did forget to mention is,

00:56:30.440 --> 00:56:36.440
[Guest 2]: the other reason he made it so difficult for women to talk was because this idea that Teddy is a family.

00:56:36.440 --> 00:56:49.440
[Guest 2]: Your workplace cannot be your family, it should not be compared to a family unit. And if someone does that, that's really problematic, because a family has a patriarch and workplaces don't need patriarchs.

00:56:49.440 --> 00:57:01.440
[Guest 2]: When you kind of start internalizing the idea that I cannot air my dirty laundry out in public, I cannot bring a bad name to the workplace I'm with, or I will be harming the cause of climate change,

00:57:01.440 --> 00:57:16.440
[Guest 2]: which was an idea that a lot of these women were told. Even after the complaint came out, I remember a horrible piece in the Guardian which tried to suggest that this was some sort of climate skeptic controversy to bring the great man of climate change down.

00:57:16.440 --> 00:57:24.440
[Guest 2]: So when you start selling us the idea that, you know, we have to operate as a family, you're bringing in all the problems of a family unit to the workplace.

00:57:24.440 --> 00:57:38.440
[Guest 2]: And I find this, that this happens with smaller workplaces a lot, that solidarity somehow is supposed to extend itself to secret keeping, which is unhealthy for your workplace, for your employees.

00:57:38.440 --> 00:57:45.440
[Guest 2]: And you know, just for the kind of culture you're developing there. Sorry, I kind of trailed off there.

00:57:45.440 --> 00:57:47.440
[Amit Varma]: No, no, no, that's a that's a fantastic point.

00:57:47.440 --> 00:57:51.440
[Guest 1]: And if you're a man or a woman who's left your family WhatsApp group, I congratulate you.

00:57:51.440 --> 00:57:58.440
[Amit Varma]: I'm kind of addicted to social media. I can't leave anything. All WhatsApp groups for me are like Hotel California.

00:57:58.440 --> 00:58:03.440
[Amit Varma]: It's also FOMO, right? What will I miss? The next sexist meme.

00:58:03.440 --> 00:58:15.440
[Amit Varma]: Nikita, I also wanted to elaborate on something you mentioned before the show started, which is that some fields, some professions are structurally more conducive to this kind of behavior.

00:58:15.440 --> 00:58:21.440
[Guest 2]: I mean, so I can speak from my experience and I am recognizing that I also come from a lot of privilege.

00:58:21.440 --> 00:58:28.440
[Guest 2]: So I feel like it may even not be representative of actually how heartbreaking journalism as a field can be.

00:58:28.440 --> 00:58:36.440
[Guest 2]: And I was working as a business reporter in Bombay. And I remember that at the time that I shifted to Delhi because I wanted to pursue political journalism,

00:58:36.440 --> 00:58:47.440
[Guest 2]: it was almost impossible for me to find an organization that would be willing to take my application seriously because it did not come from a network of patronage.

00:58:47.440 --> 00:58:53.440
[Guest 2]: Most media organizations still very recently did not have open application systems.

00:58:53.440 --> 00:58:59.440
[Guest 2]: And even now, finding out where there is a vacancy, finding out which person to meet,

00:58:59.440 --> 00:59:09.440
[Guest 2]: how you can get the interview and being taken seriously inside the room where the interview is taking place is very much a function of knowing a person who can put a good word in for you.

00:59:09.440 --> 00:59:16.440
[Guest 2]: I remember visiting at least six or seven organizations, one of which was a leading newspaper,

00:59:16.440 --> 00:59:26.440
[Guest 2]: where I remember being asked as soon as I entered that I don't have journalism experience and how I would negotiate that in the newsroom.

00:59:26.440 --> 00:59:34.440
[Guest 2]: And I remember being shocked because the first line on my resume was my journalism experience at the previous organization I'd worked with.

00:59:34.440 --> 00:59:44.440
[Guest 2]: And for that, I mean, I do want to acknowledge the caravan because I feel like that process, intensely rigorous as it is,

00:59:44.440 --> 00:59:49.440
[Guest 2]: at least gives you a sense that you're playing within a somewhat level field.

00:59:49.440 --> 00:59:56.440
[Guest 2]: You know, I was very grateful at that point because it is a long process, the caravan hiring process.

00:59:56.440 --> 01:00:06.440
[Guest 2]: But at least by the end of it, I felt like I had a chance to be meeting different kinds of people and to give it my best shot

01:00:06.440 --> 01:00:15.440
[Guest 2]: and not be given 500 minutes or not be spoken impatiently to or being told that, you know, we'll get back to you and not being gotten back to.

01:00:15.440 --> 01:00:21.440
[Guest 2]: I remember that at the point that I entered the organization, I thought that if this interview doesn't work out,

01:00:21.440 --> 01:00:30.440
[Guest 2]: I should just figure out some other career to pursue because it's just becoming untenable and I will not be able to sustain financially like this.

01:00:30.440 --> 01:00:38.440
[Guest 2]: And I think that because this network exists, because we're told that it's important to be seen with the right people,

01:00:38.440 --> 01:00:46.440
[Guest 2]: to have your byline read by the right people, to be socializing with a certain kind of hierarchy.

01:00:46.440 --> 01:00:54.440
[Guest 2]: Journalism lends itself to the secret keeping even more because you have journalists who are doing great work,

01:00:54.440 --> 01:01:00.440
[Guest 2]: who are heading great organizations that you do not want to be antagonizing.

01:01:00.440 --> 01:01:10.440
[Guest 2]: And because it is a structure within which the void between those entering the field and between those who are at the towering heights of the field is so vast

01:01:10.440 --> 01:01:14.440
[Guest 2]: that it's almost unthinkable that you're going to take that kind of machinery on.

01:01:14.440 --> 01:01:19.440
[Guest 2]: And I think that it I'm sure it is true of a variety of other fields.

01:01:19.440 --> 01:01:26.440
[Guest 2]: The reason it feels particularly hypocritical within journalism is because this is exactly the kind of, you know,

01:01:26.440 --> 01:01:30.440
[Guest 2]: idea of holding power accountable is what journalism sustains itself on.

01:01:30.440 --> 01:01:37.440
[Guest 2]: But every day is a reiteration of those power structures being enforced within this, you know, field.

01:01:37.440 --> 01:01:39.440
[Guest 2]: I don't I don't know if that.

01:01:39.440 --> 01:01:45.440
[Guest 1]: No applause. That's I mean, you've that last sentence very clearly articulated the problem with journalism.

01:01:45.440 --> 01:01:52.440
[Guest 1]: I think the last few days, if anything, have shown us that journalism is as much about concealing facts and keeping secrets as it is about revealing them.

01:01:52.440 --> 01:02:01.440
[Guest 1]: So there's a lot of work to be done for my part. I think that every industry reinforces and reiterates its power structures quite brutally in different ways.

01:02:01.440 --> 01:02:15.440
[Guest 1]: The particular way in which journalism and advertising and the entertainment industries do it is by enclosing us in this the sense of personal warmth and personal relations.

01:02:15.440 --> 01:02:23.440
[Guest 1]: Everything everything is about having apprentices who in turn have gurus who in turn will give them work.

01:02:23.440 --> 01:02:28.440
[Guest 1]: I was talking to a friend of mine who's trying to make a film who told me yesterday something we all know,

01:02:28.440 --> 01:02:33.440
[Guest 1]: which is that it doesn't matter if you have the best story and the best script in the world.

01:02:33.440 --> 01:02:38.440
[Guest 1]: If you don't have a big man opening a door for you, that door is never going to open.

01:02:38.440 --> 01:02:49.440
[Guest 1]: And while all of this may seem like huge structural issues that have very little bearing on what's going on right now in women's DMS.

01:02:49.440 --> 01:02:55.440
[Guest 1]: In fact, they are precisely at the heart of what makes it so easy to exploit women and to keep them silent.

01:02:55.440 --> 01:03:00.440
[Amit Varma]: So on one hand, the problem of access seems a gender neutral problem that men without access also face.

01:03:00.440 --> 01:03:09.440
[Guest 2]: No, I think men get that access more easily. We both were just like, no.

01:03:09.440 --> 01:03:15.440
[Amit Varma]: So I said on one hand, yeah, but on the other hand, the problem of access also perpetuates the existing gender balances,

01:03:15.440 --> 01:03:19.440
[Amit Varma]: because men are more likely to have that kind of access in the first place. Right.

01:03:19.440 --> 01:03:24.440
[Guest 1]: Oh, that's I feel like that's exactly what locker room culture is about.

01:03:24.440 --> 01:03:30.440
[Guest 1]: And from everything that we're seeing in the United States right now, it's grotesque that, you know,

01:03:30.440 --> 01:03:35.440
[Guest 1]: just being in the right locker rooms can get you some of the most powerful jobs in the land.

01:03:35.440 --> 01:03:42.440
[Guest 1]: These may not be completely obvious to us in how they operate in Indian business and politics, maybe even sports.

01:03:42.440 --> 01:03:48.440
[Guest 2]: But we know that that's the truth. And I think just again, coming back to journalism as a field, for example,

01:03:48.440 --> 01:03:56.440
[Guest 2]: who gets mentored by whom or what kind of reporter do you see as being the person who can just get to the story that is,

01:03:56.440 --> 01:04:02.440
[Guest 2]: you know, that you need to get versus a reporter who's going to be more trouble on the field.

01:04:02.440 --> 01:04:10.440
[Guest 2]: And by more trouble, I mean, when women go on the field, there are different questions of safety, of comfort, of and by comfort,

01:04:10.440 --> 01:04:17.440
[Guest 2]: I mean, the level of comfort one shares with their sources or what kind of equation the sources are going to develop with you versus when it's a man.

01:04:17.440 --> 01:04:25.440
[Guest 2]: Essentially, we're also talking about organizations within which old boys clubs still exist or the idea that you could, you know,

01:04:25.440 --> 01:04:31.440
[Guest 2]: you will step out for a drink and go to the press club. And that's when a lot of your networks and friendships are formed,

01:04:31.440 --> 01:04:36.440
[Guest 2]: which are not necessarily spaces that are very friendly to women or young women.

01:04:36.440 --> 01:04:40.440
[Guest 2]: There are also a lot of tropes that move around in these fields. Right.

01:04:40.440 --> 01:04:47.440
[Guest 2]: So it's not uncommon, for example, to hear from male journalists or like it's easier for you to get access to this report.

01:04:47.440 --> 01:04:53.440
[Guest 2]: Or maybe you found it easier to cover this story. And we know how that guy is with women.

01:04:53.440 --> 01:04:58.440
[Guest 2]: I mean, one heard this kind of vocabulary in newsrooms and has been hearing it for very long.

01:04:58.440 --> 01:05:03.440
[Guest 2]: So, you know, you'd have to change that thinking to for it to become a more accessible space.

01:05:03.440 --> 01:05:08.440
[Guest 2]: Because if and I remember experiencing this particularly in television newsrooms,

01:05:08.440 --> 01:05:16.440
[Guest 2]: where I would often wonder if the base idea is that this woman is able to get her scoop before you are because she's a woman.

01:05:16.440 --> 01:05:22.440
[Guest 2]: Then when she does get discriminated against for being a woman, why would she come and tell this office?

01:05:22.440 --> 01:05:28.440
[Guest 2]: I mean, it seems to create a prohibitive barrier to even speaking about discrimination or sexual harassment,

01:05:28.440 --> 01:05:35.440
[Guest 2]: because if I'm being discriminated within the very space in which I'm supposed to report such instances,

01:05:35.440 --> 01:05:42.440
[Guest 2]: then there's very little reason for me to have faith that these mechanisms will work.

01:05:42.440 --> 01:05:49.440
[Guest 1]: It would be remiss of me not to point out that Nikita's experiences and mine,

01:05:49.440 --> 01:05:59.440
[Guest 1]: while they represent a very particular set of challenges, in my experience, are nothing compared to what Dalit, Bahujan and Adivasi journalists face in English language newsrooms.

01:05:59.440 --> 01:06:06.440
[Guest 1]: And we haven't even begun to talk about that, which is why so if you've noticed so many Dalit women on Twitter and elsewhere have said,

01:06:06.440 --> 01:06:13.440
[Guest 1]: while we stand in solidarity with victims, you have to understand that you've made very little space in your movement for us.

01:06:13.440 --> 01:06:19.440
[Guest 1]: And I understand that. And I respect that. And I think that's something we need to introspect about.

01:06:19.440 --> 01:06:22.440
[Amit Varma]: Going back to you. And I'm just wondering if this becomes a kind of a vicious cycle here,

01:06:22.440 --> 01:06:27.440
[Amit Varma]: because you'd earlier said that women are not considered suitable for certain kinds of assignments.

01:06:27.440 --> 01:06:34.440
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time, you brought up the sort of the accounting a woman has to do whenever she goes to report a story that what should I wear?

01:06:34.440 --> 01:06:37.440
[Amit Varma]: Is it OK to have a drink with the guy in the evening if he's a source and blah, blah, blah.

01:06:37.440 --> 01:06:43.440
[Amit Varma]: And editors can easily then use this to perpetuate the same problem and say, no, no, these are stories you cannot do.

01:06:43.440 --> 01:06:47.440
[Amit Varma]: And these are stories only men can do. And it's just a vicious cycle. How do you break that?

01:06:47.440 --> 01:06:55.440
[Guest 2]: I mean, luckily, I haven't experienced that so far. At the current organization I'm with, I've been encouraged to go out on every kind of investigation possible.

01:06:55.440 --> 01:07:04.440
[Guest 2]: But I can sense that there is a lot of hesitation among women to also bring up the gendered experiences we have,

01:07:04.440 --> 01:07:12.440
[Guest 2]: because exactly like you're saying, do I really want to reinforce the idea that it's tougher for me to be out on the field?

01:07:12.440 --> 01:07:20.440
[Guest 2]: Because that is true. It's not untrue. What I think needs to change is that institutions need to recognize it not as a problem,

01:07:20.440 --> 01:07:26.440
[Guest 2]: but as something that they need to work on together with their reporters.

01:07:26.440 --> 01:07:32.440
[Guest 2]: You know, for example, an instance that comes to mind is that it so happened that two of my male colleagues

01:07:32.440 --> 01:07:36.440
[Guest 2]: and I were reporting from the same city in three successive months.

01:07:36.440 --> 01:07:42.440
[Guest 2]: So by the time I reached there, both of them had already reported on their respective stories in the same city.

01:07:42.440 --> 01:07:47.440
[Guest 2]: And they had found a hotel that they thought was, you know, relatively safe.

01:07:47.440 --> 01:07:54.440
[Guest 2]: And they suggested the hotel to me. And I remember that the minute I entered the hotel and I shut the door to my room,

01:07:54.440 --> 01:08:03.440
[Guest 2]: I realized that it didn't have a latch, you know, and it could be opened with a key, which any person in the hotel also would have access to.

01:08:03.440 --> 01:08:07.440
[Guest 2]: And I remember realizing that, of course, they didn't look for the latch.

01:08:07.440 --> 01:08:12.440
[Guest 2]: It's the first thing I look for when I enter a hotel room, because the first thought in my head is,

01:08:12.440 --> 01:08:18.440
[Guest 2]: I don't want anybody attempting to enter my room at night. I don't I want to be able to let my guard down.

01:08:18.440 --> 01:08:27.440
[Guest 2]: And it never is really down. But I think even that minute difference in how you assess a room is different between men and women.

01:08:27.440 --> 01:08:33.440
[Guest 2]: And I think it would do all of us well to recognize it and to be able to create spaces where we acknowledge it,

01:08:33.440 --> 01:08:40.440
[Guest 2]: because only then can we even think about reaching a place where incidents that lead to less women on the field can be reduced.

01:08:40.440 --> 01:08:45.440
[Guest 2]: I mean, if we don't acknowledge it, how can we address it? And I think that is a problem right now.

01:08:45.440 --> 01:08:54.440
[Guest 2]: Women are worried about speaking out because you want to be able to get all the assignments, you know, that all the men are getting as well.

01:08:54.440 --> 01:08:56.440
[Guest 2]: And I realize that really small things help, too.

01:08:56.440 --> 01:09:04.440
[Guest 2]: So, for example, for me, the knowledge that I can reach out to my editors at any point with any kind of problem I'm having on the field has greatly helped,

01:09:04.440 --> 01:09:13.440
[Guest 2]: because I'm never told that a problem is too trivial to be brought to their notice. And I don't know if all journalists have that luxury, you know.

01:09:13.440 --> 01:09:19.440
[Amit Varma]: You're also relatively lucky to be working in the caravan, which is relatively newer. Those cultures aren't there. It's not like that.

01:09:19.440 --> 01:09:26.440
[Guest 1]: I think the caravan has put in its share of hard work in rethinking how power is shaped and distributed.

01:09:26.440 --> 01:09:34.440
[Amit Varma]: So, guys, I've taken enough of your time today, so I'd like to sort of end this by asking what seems almost a banal and cliched question.

01:09:34.440 --> 01:09:41.440
[Amit Varma]: But to all the people listening to this episode, regardless of gender, whether they're men or they're women, is there something you'd like to say?

01:09:41.440 --> 01:09:48.440
[Amit Varma]: Let's say someone who hasn't really been on Twitter, hasn't really followed it to the depth that we have and doesn't have the same understanding of it.

01:09:48.440 --> 01:09:58.440
[Guest 1]: If anyone has violated your consent in the workplace or outside, or has done something that you have normalized and justified to yourself as something that you deserve to have happen to you,

01:09:58.440 --> 01:10:11.440
[Guest 1]: but that really wasn't, please don't be afraid. The fact that some women have been brave enough to speak out should be an impetus for everyone who has a story to tell

01:10:11.440 --> 01:10:23.440
[Guest 1]: and a viewpoint to share on the subject of sexual misconduct, sexual harassment, of this culture of patriarchal misbehavior that we've normalized for so long.

01:10:23.440 --> 01:10:29.440
[Guest 1]: Now is your time because you will find solidarity that you have not previously found before.

01:10:29.440 --> 01:10:35.440
[Guest 1]: If you are someone who is afraid that you are going to be accused or even falsely accused, please don't be.

01:10:35.440 --> 01:10:41.440
[Guest 1]: Please understand that this is a moment of truth and that you have every right to participate in it as much as the rest of us.

01:10:41.440 --> 01:10:53.440
[Guest 2]: I think I'd just center this on the women. I feel like I keep coming back to this, but it has really hit me that it is astonishing how exhausting it is for all of us.

01:10:53.440 --> 01:11:04.440
[Guest 2]: And if you're someone who's entering this space now, there's a fair warning that it's cathartic and it's empowering, but it's also very triggering and very exhausting.

01:11:04.440 --> 01:11:13.440
[Guest 2]: So keep your support systems near you and, you know, don't forget to remember that it's okay to switch off when you want to,

01:11:13.440 --> 01:11:26.440
[Guest 2]: because I think what we're looking at is also a collective sort of purge and it's as tough as it is, you know, hopeful for all of us involved, I think.

01:11:26.440 --> 01:11:30.440
